'''''Charmbracelet''''' is the ninth studio album by American [[singer-songwriter]] [[Mariah Carey]], released on December&nbsp;3,&nbsp;2002 through [[Island Records]] and [[MonarC Entertainment]]. The album was her first release since her breakdown following the release of her film ''[[Glitter (film)|Glitter]]'' (2001) and its [[Glitter (soundtrack)|accompanying soundtrack album]], both of which were critical and commercial failures. Critics described ''Charmbracelet'' as one of her most personal records, following 1997's ''[[Butterfly (Mariah Carey album)|Butterfly]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SL&p_theme=sl&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0FCA5DF4A394B9C3&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=Carey Puts on Her 'Charmbracelet', Hits the Road for Rare Tour|last=Johnson|first=Kevin C.|newspaper=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]|publisher=[[Lee Enterprises]]|date=July 31, 2003|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> Throughout the project, Carey collaborated with several songwriters and producers, including [[Jermaine Dupri]], [[Jimmy Jam and Terry Lewis]], [[Channel 7 (musician)|7 Aurelius]] and [[Dre & Vidal]].

According to Carey, love is the album's main theme, and the songs combine introspective and personal themes with celebration and fun.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Mariah Carey: The Truth About Her Breakdown|journal=[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]|publisher=Alpha Media Group|issn=1534-0554|location=[[New York City]]|date=December 25, 2002}}</ref> The album contains a mixture of  [[Pop music|pop]] ballads and [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] beats, and the songs incorporate elements of other genres, such as [[Gospel music|gospel]] and [[Soul music|soul]]. Compared to ''Glitter'', which featured a variety of sampled melodies from the 1980s, ''Charmbracelet'' has a more [[adult contemporary]] sound. [[Cam'ron]], [[Jay-Z]] and [[Freeway (rapper)|Freeway]] also appear on the album.

Critics gave ''Charmbracelet'' mixed reviews. Many wrote that although the songs were good, none of them stood out enough to make an impact. Some reviewers said that Carey's voice sounded thin, airy and damaged on the album. ''Charmbracelet'' debuted at number three on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart, and sold 241,000 copies in its first week. The album peaked within the top 40 in seven countries, and attained top ten positions in Japan and Switzerland.

Three singles were released to promote the album. The lead single, "[[Through the Rain]]" became the most successful, reaching the top ten in Canada, Switzerland, Sweden and Italy and the United Kingdom. In the US, it topped the [[Hot Dance Club Play]] chart, but stalled at number 81 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. The follow-ups, "Boy (I Need You)" and "Bringin' On the Heartbreak", were not as commercially successful. Carey embarked on the [[Charmbracelet World Tour: An Intimate Evening with Mariah Carey|Charmbracelet World Tour]], and performed 69 shows in over eight months. She also performed on televised shows and promotional tours like the [[American Music Awards of 2003|30th annual American Music Awards]], ''[[Today (NBC program)|Today]]'' and ''[[The Oprah Winfrey Show]]''.

==Background==
{{Quote box|quote="I had worked myself very very hard for many many years and I never took a break, and last year, I had just become very very exhausted and ended up just not really in a good place physically and emotionally. I learned a little more about how to work hard but also how to be healthy and take care of myself, and now, in general, in my life, I'm in a really good, happy place."|source=<U+2014>Carey, ''[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/sandiego/access/247811041.html?dids=247811041:247811041&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Nov+29%2C+2002&author=&pub=The+San+Diego+Union+-+Tribune&desc=The+`Glitter'+may+be+gone%2C+but+Mariah+Carey+is+coming+back+strong&pqatl=google|title=The 'Glitter' May Be Gone, But Mariah Carey Is Coming Back Strong|newspaper=[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]]|publisher=[[Platinum Equity]]|date=November 29, 2002|accessdate=June 13, 2011}}</ref>|align=right|width=30%}}

Before the release of ''Charmbracelet'', Carey experienced a year of critical, commercial, personal and professional struggles, following the poor reception of her debut film ''[[Glitter (film)|Glitter]]'' (2001), and her subsequent hospitalization.<ref name=careyon>{{cite news|url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/boston/access/983024561.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Feb+05%2C+2006&author=Joan+Anderman%2C+GLOBE+STAFF&pub=Boston+Globe&desc=CAREY%2C+ON!&pqatl=google|title=Carey, On!|last=Anderson|first=Joan|work=[[The Boston Globe]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|date=February 6, 2006|accessdate=May 13, 2011}}</ref> After divorcing her husband, [[Tommy Mottola]], Carey released ''[[Butterfly (Mariah Carey album)|Butterfly]]'' (1997).<ref name="Mayer">{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/arts/music/carey.html|title=Carey On|last=Meyer|first=Andre|work=[[CBC News]]|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]]|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20110628230719/http://www.cbc.ca/arts/music/carey.html|archivedate=June 28, 2011|accessdate=February 24, 2011|date=December 13, 2005}}</ref> With her next release, ''[[Rainbow (Mariah Carey album)|Rainbow]]'' (1999), Carey incorporated elements of [[R&B]] and [[hip hop music|hip-hop]] into her music, particularly on the lead single "[[Heartbreaker (Mariah Carey song)|Heartbreaker]]".<ref name="Mayer"/> According to ''[[The Sacramento Bee]]'', she attempted to sound more "ghetto".<ref name=mam>{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SB&p_theme=sb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=10F9B7020EDCCB58&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=Mariah Carey Survived a Year Turn Down to Become the Year's Comeback Queen|newspaper=[[The Sacramento Bee]]|publisher=[[The McClatchy Company]]|date=February 6, 2006|accessdate=August 2, 2011}}</ref> She stopped working with longtime pop producers such as [[Babyface (musician)|Babyface]] and [[Walter Afanasieff]], in order to pursue a new sound and audience, and worked with writers [[Sean Combs]] and [[Jermaine Dupri]].<ref name=mam/> Following the worldwide success of  ''Rainbow'', Carey left [[Columbia Records]].<ref name="Vineyard">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/bands/c/carey_mariah/news_feature_032805/index.jhtml|title=Bands A-Z: Mariah Carey|work=[[MTV]]|publisher=[[MTV Networks]] ([[Viacom]])|accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref> Controversially, Mottola and executive [[Benny Medina]] in 1999 used several songs Carey had written and co-written for [[Jennifer Lopez]].<ref name="Vineyard"/> Carey's 2001 film debut ''Glitter''<ref name="Mayer"/><ref name="Vineyard"/> was panned by movie critics, and earned less than eight million dollars at the box office.<ref name="Mayer"/><ref name="Vineyard"/> The soundtrack fared slightly better, spawned a top-five single in the United States and sold over three million units globally.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.store.livenation.com/Product.aspx?cp=13281_25619_25593_25883_29557&pc=MUDD556|title=Live Nation&nbsp;<U+2013> Mariah Carey: Glitter|work=[[Live Nation]]|publisher=[[Live Nation Entertainment]]|accessdate=August 24, 2010}}</ref>

Carey's $100&nbsp;million recording contract was bought out by [[Virgin Records]], who paid her $28&nbsp;million to leave the label.<ref name="Mayer"/> Carey checked into a hospital in Connecticut, following a controversial appearance on ''[[Total Request Live]]'', in which she gave ice cream to fans, left troubling messages on her website and demonstrated what was considered by the media as "erratic behavior".<ref name=careyon/><ref name=hospital>{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=JTIzAAAAIBAJ&sjid=kwgGAAAAIBAJ&pg=6593,3086458&dq=mariah+carey+breakdown&hl=en|title=Mariah Carey Released After Breakdown|work=[[The Free Lance<U+2013>Star]]|publisher=The Free Lance<U+2013>Star Publishing Company|date=August 9, 2001|accessdate=June 15, 2011}}</ref> Carey said she had had an "emotional and physical breakdown."<ref name=hospital/> After a fortnight's hospitalization, Carey flew to [[Capri]], Italy, where she stayed for five months and began writing and producing material for a new studio album about her recent troubles.<ref name=hospital/> She was signed by [[Island Records]], and started her own imprint, [[MonarC Entertainment]], for her intended "comeback" release, ''Charmbracelet''.<ref name="Vineyard"/>

==Development and recording==
{{Quote box | quote = "The experience of recording this album is almost like the experience of my life{{emdash}}going through it dealing with things and trying to be hopeful. It's not an album filled with woe and misery. There are some songs that will give you that melancholy feeling, but I try to always go to the uplifting even in a situation that seems that it could break you. I try to always turn to the positive rather than drown in the negative."|source=<U+2014>Carey on the album's sound to ''[[R&R (magazine)|Radio and Records]]''<ref name="r&r"/>|align=left|width=250px}}
Carey started writing songs for the album in early 2002,<ref name="r&r">{{cite journal|title =Mariah's Back Fresh, Focused and Full of Hits|journal=[[R&R (magazine)|Radio and Records]]|publisher=Radio & Records, Inc.|last=Novia|first=Tony|date=September 27, 2002|issn=1076-6502|location=[[Los Angeles, California]]}}</ref> before she signed the record deal.<ref name="bbimp"/> She decided to rest,<ref>{{cite news|title=Recharged Carey Begins Anew|newspaper=[[Rocky Mountain News|The Rocky Mountain News]]|publisher=[[E. W. Scripps Company]]|date=December 6, 2002|location=[[Denver]]}}</ref> traveled to Capri and moved into a recording studio<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.corriere.it/Primo_Piano/Spettacoli/2002/05_Maggio/26/carey.shtml|title =Disco a Capri per Mariah Carey|newspaper=[[Corriere della Sera]]|publisher=[[RCS MediaGroup]]|date=May 26, 2002|location=Capri, [[Naples]]|language=Italian|accessdate=August 16, 2011}}</ref> where she could focus on writing and recording without distractions.<ref name="r&r"/><ref name="ref1">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1458761/mariah-remakes-camron-song.jhtml|title=Mariah remakes Cam'ron song, Drops Timberlake from New LP|last1=Reid|first1=Shaheem|last2=Cornell|first2=Jeff|work=MTV|publisher=MTV Networks (Viacom)|date=November 19, 2002|accessdate=August 16, 2011}}</ref> Most of the album was recorded in Capri, although she traveled to Atlanta, New York and Philadelphia to record some tracks.<ref name="b&s">{{cite journal|title=The Second Coming of Mariah Carey|journal=[[Blues & Soul]]|year=2002|location=[[Croydon]]|last=Jennings|first=Helen|issn=0959-6550}}</ref> That year, Carey claimed ''Charmbracelet'' to be the "most personal album" she had ever made.<ref name="ref1"/> She worked with longtime collaborators Jermaine Dupri, [[Jimmy Jam and Terry Lewis]] and [[Randy Jackson]]<ref name="bbimp">{{cite journal|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=Og0EAAAAMBAJ|title=Carey Eager to Start a Fresh Chapter|journal=Billboard|publisher=[[Nielsen Company|Nielsen Business Media, Inc.]]|last=Flick|first=Larry|page=3|volume=114|issue=49|issn=0006-2510|date=December 7, 2002|accessdate=August 16, 2011}}</ref> and other songwriters and producers [[7 Aurelius]], Just Blaze, [[Damizza]] and [[Dre & Vidal]].<ref name="bbimp"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/news/articles/1456879/new-mariah-album-december.jhtml|title=Mariah returning with First Def Jam Release in December|last=Oh|first=Minya|work=[[VH1]]|publisher=MTV Networks (Viacom)|accessdate=August 16, 2011}}</ref> The opening track and the first track to be written for the album,<ref name="b&s"/> "[[Through the Rain]]", was written by Carey and [[Lionel Cole]],<ref name=allmusic/> was inspired Carey's recent experiences,<ref name="mtv1">{{cite web|url =http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1457873/mariah-dont-call-it-comeback.jhtml|title =Mariah Carey Insists She Just Needed Sleep, Taps Family History for Clip|last1=Reid|first1=Shaheem|last2=Norris|first2=John|work=MTV|publisher=MTV Networks (Viacom)|date=October 1, 2002|accessdate=August 16, 2011}}</ref> and was co-produced by Jam and Lewis. It was released as the [[lead single]] from the album.<ref name=allmusic/>

Jam, Lewis and Carey also worked "Yours", which Jam said contains "probably one of the best hooks [ever]", and likened it to one of trio's previous collaborations, "[[Thank God I Found You]]" (2000).<ref name="mtv1"/> Initially, the song was recorded as duet with pop singer [[Justin Timberlake]].<ref>{{cite web|url =http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,365138,00.html|title ='Yours' Truly|last=Susman|first=Gary|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time Warner]]|date=October 16, 2002|accessdate=August 16, 2011}}</ref> However, due to contractual complications, it was never released and the a solo version was featured on the album.<ref name="mtv2">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1458130/justin-records-mariah-lp.jhtml|title=Timberlake, Jay-Z, Cam'ron contribute to Mariah Carey LP|last=Moss|first=Corey|work=MTV|publisher=MTV Networks (Viacom)|date=October 15, 2002|accessdate=August 16, 2011}}</ref> Jam and Lewis produced two more songs, "Wedding Song" and "Satisfy"{{emdash}}the latter featuring background vocals from [[Michael Jackson]]{{emdash}}which were not released on the album.<ref name="mtv2"/><ref>{{harvnb|Halstead|Cadman|2003|p=193}}</ref>

Carey decided to work with [[Just Blaze]] after she heard the song "[[Oh Boy (song)|Oh Boy]]", which he produced for [[Cam'ron]].<ref name="ref1"/> Just Blaze and Carey  produced "[[Boy (I Need You)]]", a remake of "Oh Boy", and "You Got Me".<ref name="ref1"/> Carey said "Boy (I Need You)" was one of her favorites on the album.<ref name="ref1"/> "You Got Me" features rap verses from [[Jay-Z]] and [[Freeway (rapper)|Freeway]], was noted by Carey as a "signature Just Blaze track".<ref name="ref1"/> Jay-Z was in Capri on  vacation, and went to the studio to hear the song and said that he wanted to contribute to it and added rap verses of his own.<ref name="ref1"/> Dupri produced "The One" and "You Had Your Chance". He said that they wanted to stick to the "same familiar sound" from his previous collaborations with Carey.<ref>{{cite web|url =http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1453868/mariah-signs-with-islanddef-jam.jhtml|title =Mariah Signs with Island/Def Jam, Records with JD|last1=Reid|first1=Shaheem|last2=Calloway|first2=Sway|work=MTV|publisher=MTV Networks (Viacom)|date=May 8, 2002|accessdate=August 16, 2011}}</ref> Carey said "The One" was a personal song, which was about being hurt in past relationships and the uncertainty about forming new ones.<ref name="ref1"/> Carey decided to experiment with a live band for the album.<ref name="mtv3">{{cite web|url =http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1453479/mariah-carey-recording-new-music.jhtml|title=Mariah Carey Records in Bahamas with Live Band, Strips Down with 7|last=Reid|first=Shaheem|work=MTV|publisher=MTV Networks (Viacom)|date=April 18, 2002|accessdate=August 16, 2011}}</ref> In April 2002, she met 7 Aurelius and asked him to produce songs for the album. They flew to [[Nassau, Bahamas]] and recorded a mixture of mid-tempo and up-tempo tracks and ballads with a live band. 7 Aurelius said that Carey was "an amazing writer" and described the process of recording:

<blockquote>
We did three or four songs in three or four days. The way we was doing it, I had [a horn section] down there along with me. We had the whole room set up with candles, some nice wine{{emdash}}[it was] a very good vibe. It was completely stripped down, like 'Mariah Carey Unplugged'. She stripped herself down to her talent. She was really trusting of me and my vision, and I was trusting of who she was.<ref name="mtv3"/>
</blockquote>

{{Quote box |quote = "Charm bracelets have always had a personal and sentimental significance for me. Charms are like pieces of yourself that you pass on to other people, items that tell your story and that can be shared, like a song. The bracelet represents the foundation of this album, a body of work that encompasses many feelings."|source=<U+2014>Carey on the title of the album, ''Charmbracelet''.<ref>{{cite web|url =http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1458228/.jhtml|title =For the Record: Quick News on Mariah Carey, Britney Spears, 'American Idol', Jewel, Outkast, Kenna, Garbage & More|work=[[MTV]]|publisher=MTV Networks (Viacom)|date=October 18, 2002|accessdate=August 16, 2011}}</ref>|align=right|width=300px}}

Randy Jackson contributed to four tracks on the album, and said it was "the most real and honest record she's made. She didn't care what anyone thought of the lyrics. They were only important to her."<ref>{{cite web|url =http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,66464,00.html|title =Mariah Does Def Leppard Cover|last=Friedman|first=Roger|date=October 23, 2002|work=[[Fox News]]|publisher=[[News Corporation]]|accessdate=August 16, 2011}}</ref> Carey included a cover of  [[Def Leppard]]'s song "[[Bringin' On the Heartbreak]]". During the photo shoot for ''Charmbracelet'' at Capri, Carey happened to listen to Def Leppard's album ''[[Vault: Def Leppard Greatest Hits (1980<U+2013>1995)|Vault]]'' (1995), which contains the song, and decided to cover it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.music.yahoo.ca/read/news/12026730|title=Mariah Carey Says She Loves Def Leppard Cover|work=[[Yahoo! Launch]]|publisher=Yahoo Inc|date=2003-06-30|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6Dae1a7wQ|archivedate=2013-01-11|accessdate=2013-01-11}}</ref> In an interview with ''Billboard'', Carey said that the song is "an example of her musical diversity".<ref name="bbimp"/> Jackson also worked on "My Saving Grace", which Carey said describes her thoughts about the writing, recording and mastering process.<ref name="mtv1"/> While working in Capri, Carey's father<ref>{{cite journal|title=Mariah Writes 'Sunflower' for Dad|work=Network Magazine|publisher=Clear Channel Network Magazines Group|location=[[Burbank, California]]|date=October 17, 2002}}</ref> became ill with cancer and she returned to New York to spend some time with him;<ref>{{cite news|title =Home to Daddy|newspaper=[[New York Post]]|publisher=News Corporation|page=Page Six|date=June 14, 2002}}</ref><ref name="interviewm">{{cite journal |last=Sischy |first=Ingrid |date=September 2007 |title=Mariah Carey: The Naked Truth from the World's Biggest Diva |journal=[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]] |page=162 |publisher=[[Brant Publications]] |issn=0149-8932}}</ref> he died soon after.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mariah's Dad Dies Holding Her Hand|work=[[Daily Mirror|The Mirror]]|publisher=[[Trinity Mirror]]|date=July 13, 2002}}</ref> In his memory, Carey wrote and produced the song "Sunflowers for Alfred Roy".<ref name="interviewm"/> Carey said that the song represents "his side of the family and is kind of hard to talk about."<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Interview with Mariah Carey |accessdate=August 17, 2011 |series=Larry King Live |serieslink=Larry King Live |credits=[[Larry King]] (presenter); Mariah Carey (guest) |network=''[[CNN]]'' |airdate=2002-12-19 |time=21:00 ([[Eastern Time Zone|EST]]) |transcripturl=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0212/19/lkl.00.html|language=English}}</ref> The song proved to be "very emotional" for Carey, and she sang it only once in the studio.<ref name="bbimp"/> [[DJ Quik]] also produced songs for the album, but none of them were included.<ref name=allmusic/><ref>{{cite web|url =http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1453558/mariah-records-with-dj-quik.jhtml|title=Mariah Goes from Murder Inc. to the Club with DJ Quik|last=Reid|first=Shaheem|work=MTV|publisher=MTV Networks (Viacom)|date=April 23, 2002|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref>

==Music and lyrics==
{{Listen
| filename=Mariah Carey - Subtle Invitation.ogg
| title="Subtle Invitation"
| description=A sample of the song's bridge, which makes usage of a live orchestral band. With the chorus speaking of loyalty to an ex-lover through difficult times, Carey's energy increases towards the song's finale, leading to a heightened [[Key (music)|key]].<ref name=guardian/>
| format=[[Ogg]]
}}
Carey attempted to make a musical comeback with ''Charmbracelet'',<ref name=ladailynews>{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=LA&p_theme=la&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0F7D5D9354BB9099&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=Sound Check|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Daily News]]|publisher=[[MediaNews Group]]|date=December 6, 2002|accessdate=June 13, 2011|subscription=yes}}</ref> which focused on bringing Carey back to her [[adult contemporary]] roots in an attempt to recapture her audience.<ref name=ladailynews/> Critics both praised and criticized the condition of Carey's voice on the album; many called the songs average, and felt that most lacked sufficient [[Hook (music)|hook]]s.<ref name=ladailynews/> The album's lead single, and Carey's boldest attempt at recreating the ballads from the early years of her career, was "Through the Rain",<ref name=ladailynews/> which was produced by Carey, and was described by one critic as "the sort of self-help ballad Ms. Carey was singing a decade ago".<ref name=Sanneh>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2002/12/01/movies/music-when-you-fall-you-get-back-up.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm|title=Music; When You Fall, You Get Back Up|first=Kelefa |last=Sanneh |work=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=December 1, 2002|accessdate=June 13, 2011}}</ref> The songs on the album are a mixture of several genres.

Carey's cover of "Bringin' On the Heartbreak", was recorded using live instrumentation, and was the album's third single.<ref name=Sanneh/> It begins as a "piano-driven slow jam", which is followed by a "dramatic [[chord progression]]" after the second chorus, and Carey's "precise and fluttery voice reaches incredible heights" as it "turns the power ballad into something more delicate."<ref name=Sanneh/> [[Kelefa Sanneh]] from [[The New York Times]] called "Yours"{{sp}}"a delectable combination of breathy vocals and playful rhythms."<ref name=Sanneh/> Barry Walters from ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' wrote that on "Yours", "Carey's lead vocals blend into choruses of overdubbed Mariah's cooing overlapping phrases. Circling these are choirs of more Mariahs singing harmonies and countermelodies. Topping it off are generous sprinklings of the singer's patented birdcalls, wails, sighs and whispers."<ref name=rsreview>{{cite web|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/charmbracelet-20021119|title=Mariah Carey: Charmbracelet|last=Walters|first=Barry|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|publisher=[[Jann Wenner|Wenner Media]]|date=November 19, 2002|accessdate=June 13, 2011}}</ref>

{{Quote box|quote="Her carefully assembled new album resembles a computer preset in its soulless precision. But there's a reason. This tin ''Charmbracelet'' is a throwback to the soft and fuzzy Mariah the masses succumbed to in the 1990s before she began competing with DMX for street credibility. To bring in the customers, Carey delivers her parts here in the familiar high-pitched coo, sort of Minnie Riperton without soul, backed by just-press-play synth-strings and soft, sparkly keyboards."|source=<U+2014>A writer from ''[[Los Angeles Daily News]]'' describing the album's production and vocals as a whole.<ref name=ladailynews/>|align=left|width=30%}}

Critics considered "Subtle Invitation" to be one of the album's strongest songs because of its "well executed" jazz influence. The song begins with the sounds of people dining, then introduces the strong bassline and drums. Towards the end of the song, Carey belts out the climax. Sarah Rodman from ''[[The Boston Herald]]'' described it as fascinating and wrote, "it sounds as though Carey is singing in falsetto while still in her chest voice."<ref name=boston/> "Clown" drew strong media attention, and its lyrical content led critics to speculate that Carey aimed it at rapper [[Eminem]], who had publicly announced that he had had a relationship with Carey. Rodman said "Clown" was "languidly sinister", with lyrics such as, "I should've left it at 'I like your music too'&nbsp;...&nbsp;You should never have intimated we were lovers / when you know very well we never even touched each other."<ref name=boston>{{cite news|url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/bostonherald/access/250796631.html?dids=250796631:250796631&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Dec+03%2C+2002&author=Sarah+Rodman&pub=Boston+Herald&desc=Carey+hopes+promotion+efforts+work+like+a+charm&pqatl=google|title=Carey Hopes Promotion Efforts Work Like a Charm |last=Rodman |first=Sarah |work=The Boston Globe |publisher=The New York Times Company |date=December 3, 2002 |accessdate=June 13, 2011|subscription=yes}}</ref> Critics compared "I Only Wanted" with "[[My All]]"{{'}}s instrumentation and structure of verse, chorus and guitar solo. According to Sal Cinquemani from [[Slant Magazine]], Carey makes vague allusions to her ex-husband Tommy Mottola with the line, "Wish I'd stayed beneath my veil".<ref name=slantreview/> The song uses Latin-inspired guitar instrumentation and wind sounds as an additional backbone to the melody, and dripping water as its percussion.<ref name=allmusic>{{cite web|last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/charmbracelet-r617273/review|title=Charmbracelet > Overview|work=[[Allmusic]]|publisher=[[Rovi Corporation]]|date=December 3, 2002|accessdate=June 13, 2011}}</ref>

"Sunflowers for Alfred Roy", one of the album's most personal songs, is named after Carey's father; she makes direct reference to him and a moment they shared at his death bed.<ref name=Sanneh/><ref name=ewreview/> The song is backed with a simple piano accompaniment, and Carey recounts a visit with her father in his hospital room: "Strange to feel that proud, strong man / Grip tightly to my hand."<ref name=Sanneh/><ref name=ewreview/>

==Singles==
{{Listen
| filename=Mariah Carey - Bringin' On The Heartbreak.ogg
| title="Bringin' On the Heartbreak"
| description= A 27-second sample of "Bringin' On the Heartbreak", featuring the guitar solo used to link the second chorus to the song's climax. The [[Bridge (music)|bridge]] is followed by Carey's usage of her upper vocal registers.
}}
Three singles were released from the album. The lead single, "Through the Rain" was released on September 24, 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/through-the-rain-r617283|title=Through the Rain&nbsp;<U+2013> Mariah Carey|publisher=Allmusic. Rovi Corporation|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> It received mixed reviews from critics, some of whom said it was too similar to her earlier ballads, such as "[[Hero (Mariah Carey song)|Hero]]" and "Outside",<ref>{{cite news|title=They Call the Wind: Carey's Comeback album offers the same old sentimental, 'show-offy' approach|newspaper=New York Daily News|publisher=Mortimer Zuckerman|date=December 1, 2002|last=Farber|first=Jim|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/2535321.stm|title=Carey's charm offensive|last=Levell|first=Tim|date=December 2, 2002|publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> while others praised Carey's vocals in the song.<ref name=ewreview/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.usatoday.com/life/music/reviews/2002-12-02-charmbracelet_x.htm|title=Carey Sounds Like Gold on 'Charmbracelet'|last=Gardner|first=Elysa|newspaper=USA Today|publisher=Gannett Company|date=December 2, 2002|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/mariah-carey-charmbracelet/250|title=Mariah Carey: Charmbracelet|last=Cinquemani|first=Sal|publisher=Slant Magazine|date=November 19, 2002|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> It was one of Carey's poorest-selling US singles, reaching number 81 on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart. However, it topped the [[Hot Dance Club Play]] charts and reached the top twenty of the [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Adult Contemporary]] chart.<ref name="singles">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/charmbracelet-r617273/charts-awards/billboard-single|title=Charmbracelet&nbsp;<U+2013> Mariah Carey > Singles|publisher=Allmusic. Rovi Corporation|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> Outside the US, the single performed moderately, peaking within the top ten in Canada, Switzerland, Sweden, Italy and the UK,<ref name="ttr"/> and within the top 20 in Ireland, Australia, Norway and Denmark.<ref name="ttr">{{cite web|url=http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Mariah+Carey&titel=Through+The+Rain&cat=s|title=Mariah Carey&nbsp;<U+2013> Charmbracelet|work=ARIA Charts|publisher=Hung Medien|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> The music video of "Through the Rain", directed by Daver Meyers, is based on the courtship and eloping of Carey's parents. Scenes of Carey singing in a street when rain starts to fall are juxtaposed with the story of a mixed-race couple who run away from their families, who oppose their relationship.<ref>{{cite episode|title=Music Video Premieres|network=MTV|date=October 19, 2002}}</ref>

"Boy (I Need You)", which was released as the second single on November 26, 2002,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/boy-i-need-you-12-single-r619712|title=Boy I Need You <nowiki>[12" Single]</nowiki>|publisher=Allmusic. Rovi Corporation|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> received mixed reviews from critics.<ref name=allmusic/><ref name=ewreview/> The single failed to make much impact on charts worldwide; it reached number 68 on the US ''Billboard'' Hip-Hop/R&B Songs chart and number 57 on the US Hot Singles Sales chart.<ref name="singles"/> Elsewhere, the song reached number 17 in the UK, and peaked within the top 40 in Australia,<ref>{{cite web|url =http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Mariah+Carey+feat.+Cam%27Ron&titel=Boy+%28I+Need+You%29&cat=s|title=Mariah Carey feat. Cam'Ron&nbsp;<U+2013> Boy (I Need You)|work=ARIA Charts|publisher=Hung Medien|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> the Netherlands, Ireland and New Zealand.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Mariah+Carey&titel=Boy+%28I+Need+You%29&cat=s|title=Mariah Carey&nbsp;<U+2013> Boy (I Need You)|work=Dutch Top 40|publisher=Hung Medien|language=Dutch|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> The music video for "Boy (I Need You)" was directed by [[Joseph Kahn]] and was filmed at [[Shibuya]] and [[Los Angeles]]. Initially, "The One" was scheduled to be released as the second single and the music video was shot for that song.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=0yYEAAAAMBAJ|title=Through the Fire|last=Ogunnaike|first=Lola|date=March 2003|page=114|volume=11|issue=3|journal=[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]|publisher=[[InterMedia Partners]]|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> However, halfway through the filming, the single was changed to "Boy (I Need You)".<ref name="mvpa">{{cite web|url=http://www.mvpa.com/articles/mariahvideo.htm|title=Mariah Carey Video Article|last=Rushing|first=Brad|publisher=[[Music Video Production Association]]|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20040609055523/http://www.mvpa.com/articles/mariahvideo.htm|archivedate=June 9, 2004|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> Described as "Speed Racer meets Hello Kitty meets me and Cam'ron" by Carey,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1459550/mariah-camron-shoot-video.jhtml|title=Mariah, Cam'ron Shoot 'Speed Racer Meets Hello Kitty' Video|last=Moss|first=Carey|work=MTV|publisher=MTV Networks (Viacom)|date=June 16, 2003|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> the video incorporates elements of Japanese culture and features Carey's alter-ego Bianca.<ref name="mvpa"/>

The third single from the album was Carey's cover version of "Bringin' on the Heartbreak", released on November 25, 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://allmusic.com/album/bringin-on-the-heartbreak-r670416|title=Bringin' on the Heartbreak&nbsp;<U+2013> Mariah Carey|publisher=Allmusic. Rovi Corporation|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> Though it gained mostly positive reviews,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.sfgate.com/2002-12-11/entertainment/17573856_1_whitney-houston-mariah-carey-charmbracelet|title=Tracks of their tears|last=Chonin|first=Neva|work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|publisher=[[Hearst Corporation]]|date=December 11, 2002|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=BC&p_theme=bc&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0F87A0FF532F7EA2&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=Tuned In|last=Campbell|first=Chuck|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|publisher=[[Sun-Times Media Group]]|date=December 24, 2002|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/charmbracelet-20021119|title=Charmbracelet by Mariah Carey|last=Walters|first=Barry|date=November 19, 2002|work=Rolling Stone |publisher=Wenner Media|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> it failed to chart on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100, but reached number five on the Hot Dance Club Play chart.<ref name="singles"/> Outside the US, the song saw its highest peak in Switzerland, reaching number 28 and staying on the charts for eight weeks.<ref name="both">{{cite web|url=http://swisscharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Mariah+Carey&titel=Bringin%27+On+The+Heartbreak&cat=s|title=Mariah Carey&nbsp;<U+2013> Bringin' on the Heartbreak|work=<U+00D6>3 Austria Top 40|publisher=Hung Medien|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> It also charted in Austria and the Wallonia region of Belgium.<ref name="both"/> The music video for the song was directed by [[Sanaa Hamri]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv-ca-jq.mtvi.com/music/video_browse_play.jhtml?vid=22733&aid=976|title=Mariah Carey: Bringin' on the Heartbreak|publisher=[[MTV Canada]]. MTV Networks (Viacom)|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> Another cut from the album, "Irresistible (Westside Connection)" charted at number 81 on the US ''Billboard'' Hip-Hop/R&B Songs.<ref name="singles"/>

==Critical reception==
{{Album ratings
| MC  = 43/100<ref name="metac"/>
<!-- Reviewers -->
| rev1 = [[Allmusic]]
