| rev2 = ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''
| rev2Score = favorable<ref name=review>{{cite journal|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=MQ0EAAAAMBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Reviews and Previews: Spotlights|last=Paoletta|first=Michael|journal=Billboard|publisher=[[Nielsen Company|Nielsen Business Media, Inc.]]|date=December 16, 2002|volume=114|issue=51|issn=0006-2510|page=29|accessdate=June 14, 2011}}</ref>
| rev3 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''
| rev3Score = C<ref name=ewreview/>
| rev4 = ''[[The Guardian]]''
| rev4Score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref name=guardian>{{cite news|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/2002/nov/29/popandrock.artsfeatures4|title=Mariah Carey: Charmbracelet|last=Lynskey|first=Dorian|work=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]|date=November 29, 2002|accessdate=June 14, 2011}}</ref>
| rev5 = ''[[The New York Times]]''
| rev5Score = favorable<ref name=Sanneh/>
| rev6 = ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]''
| rev6Score = unfavorable<ref name=pop>{{cite web|url=http://nymag.com/nymetro/arts/music/pop/reviews/n_8132/|title=Mariah Carey: Charmbracelet|last=Brown|first=Ethan|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|publisher=New York Media Holdings|date=August 9, 2005|accessdate=February 21, 2010}}</ref>
| rev7 = ''[[NME]]''
| rev7Score = unfavorable<ref name=nme>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/mariah-carey/6889|title=Mariah Carey: Charmbracelet: A Disappointingly Sane Comeback|last=Mulvey|first=John|work=[[NME]]|publisher=[[IPC Media]]|location=UK|date=December 13, 2002|accessdate=June 16, 2011}}</ref>
| rev8 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''
| rev8Score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref name=rsreview/>
| rev9 = [[Slant Magazine]]
| rev9Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=slantreview>{{cite web|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/mariah-carey-charmbracelet|title=Mariah Carey: Charmbracelet|last=Cinquemani|first=Sal|publisher=[[Slant Magazine]]|date=November 19, 2002|accessdate=June 13, 2011}}</ref>
| rev10 = [[Yahoo! Music|Yahoo! Music UK]]
| rev10Score = {{Rating|4|10}}<ref name=yahoouk>{{cite web|url=http://uk.launch.yahoo.com/l_reviews_a/27568.html|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20110613162408/http://uk.launch.yahoo.com/l_reviews_a/27568.html|archivedate=2011-06-13|title=Mariah Carey: Charmbracelet|last=Batey|first=Angus|publisher=[[Yahoo! Music|Yahoo! Music UK]]. [[Yahoo!]]|date=December 9, 2002 |accessdate=June 13, 2011}}</ref>
}}
Upon its release, critics gave ''Charmbracelet'' mixed reviews. The main criticism concerned its content; many reviewers felt that although the songs were good, none stood out enough to make much of an impact on radio or the market. Some critics were concerned about the condition of Carey's voice, which they felt had become thin, airy and damaged when compared to her vocals throughout the early 1990s. Review aggregator [[Metacritic]], which averages professional reviews into a numerical score, gave the album 43/100, indicating "generally mixed or average reviews."<ref name="metac">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/charmbracelet|title=Charmbracelet&nbsp;<U+2013> Mariah Carey|work=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=February 5, 2011}}</ref> [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] from [[Allmusic]] rated the album two out of five stars, and criticized its production and the condition of Carey's voice.<ref name=allmusic/> He wrote, "Whenever she sings, there's a raspy whistle behind her thin voice and she strains to make notes throughout the record&nbsp;...&nbsp;Her voice is damaged, and there's not a moment where it sounds strong or inviting."<ref name=allmusic/> Tom Sinclair of  ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' said she was "in fine voice", He wrote that "Through the Rain" sinks in its own sodden sentimentality, as do by-the-numbers efforts like 'Yours' and 'I Only Wanted'{{sp}}", and added that "{{'}}Clown' is a moody number graced with mournful acoustic guitar and a gorgeously nuanced vocal, while 'Sunflowers for Alfred Roy' is a short, sweet song sung to a lovely piano accompaniment". He finished by saying that "too much of ''Charmbracelet'' is mired in middle-of-the-road muck."<ref name=ewreview>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,397173,00.html|title=Mariah Carey: Charmbracelet|last=Sinclair|first=Tom|work=Entertainment Weekly|publisher=Time Warner|date=December 9, 2002|accessdate=June 13, 2011}}</ref>

''Billboard'' editor Michael Paoletta praised Carey's return to her adult contemporary beginnings.<ref name=review/> He said that although Carey might have alienated her hip-hop followers from her previous three albums, her older fans from the 1990s would be more receptive to the material and her new image.<ref name=review/> Kelefa Sanneh from ''The New York Times'' wrote that the album "is generally pleasant, although it's not always exciting, and a few of the collaborations go awry". He called Carey's voice "invariably astonishing", and said that "she can hit high notes that barely sound human", praised her versatility, and wrote that she "also knows how to make a hip-hop hit by holding back and letting the beat shine."<ref name=Sanneh/> Ethan Browne of ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' slated the album's whimsical chimes and tinkling keyboards, and wrote, "Was Charmbracelet recorded in a Casio shop? This instrument needs to be stopped."<ref name=pop/>

Rating ''Charmbracelet'' two out of five stars, Barry Walters from ''Rolling Stone'' wrote that none of the songs were bold, that the lack of hooks made the album weak, and said, "Carey needs bold songs that help her use the power and range for which she is famous. Charmbracelet is like a stream of watercolors that bleed into a puddle of brown."<ref name=rsreview/> Sal Cinquemani from Slant Magazine complimented Carey's mixture of pop and hip-hop melodies, and wrote, "Though there's nothing as immediate as 'Fantasy' or 'My All' here, Charmbracelet is significantly less contrived than 1999's ''Rainbow'' and almost as creatively liberating as ''Butterfly''.<ref name=slantreview/> British columnist Angus Batey, writing for [[Yahoo! Music|Yahoo! Music UK]] called the songs on ''Charmbracelet'' forgettable, and wrote, "She used to take risks, but 'Charmbracelet' is conservative, unadventurous and uninspiring; and, while it's understandable that simply to make another record marks a triumph of sorts, it's impossible to admire Mariah to the degree that her talent ought to merit."<ref name=yahoouk/> John Mulvey from ''[[NME]]'' criticized its content, writing, "Nominally, 'Charmbracelet' is R&B, much like Tony Blair is nominally a socialist&nbsp;...&nbsp;Tragedies, all told, have been worse"<ref name=nme/>

==Commercial performance==
[[File:Mariah Carey Charmbracelet London.jpg|thumb|left|Carey and her dancers performing "Heartbreaker" on the Charmbracelet Tour in 2003|alt=A blonde woman wearing a white top and short skirt sings. She is flanked by four men, who pretend to take photographs of her.]]

''Charmbracelet'' was initially slated for release in the US on December 10, 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url =http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,392496~4~0~justinbreakshisfoot,00.html|title=Cry Me a River|last=Susman|first=Gary|work=Entertainment Weekly|publisher=Time Warner|date=November 20, 2002|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> However, the date was revised to December 3, 2002. It was released through Island Records and Carey's label MonarC Entertainment.<ref name=guardian/><ref name=allmusic/> A highly anticipated release,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/USAToday/access/268326911.html?dids=268326911:268326911&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Dec+12%2C+2002&author=Edna+Gundersen&pub=USA+TODAY&desc=%27Charmbracelet%27+ranks+third&pqatl=google|title='Charmbracelet' ranks third|last=Gundersen|first=Edna|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|publisher=[[Gannett Company]]|date=December 12, 2002|page=D.01|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url =http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/nypost/access/270027591.html?dids=270027591:270027591&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Dec+19%2C+2002&author=Mary+Huhn&pub=New+York+Post&desc=WHITNEY+%26+MARIAH+WEAK&pqatl=google|title =Whitney & Mariah Weak|last=Huhn|first=Mary|newspaper=New York Post|publisher=News Corporation|page=064|date=December 19, 2002|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> it debuted at number three on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], with first-week sales of 241,000,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://login.vnuemedia.com/bbbiz/search/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1776934|title=Mariah's Charms Unable to Send Shania's 'Up' Down|last=Martens|first=Todd|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc|date=December 11, 2002|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> more than the first-week sales of the critically panned ''Glitter'' soundtrack,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/266419/artists-of-the-decade-page-two|title=Artists of the Decade|page=2|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> but fewer than 1999's ''Rainbow'', which sold 323,000 units in its first week.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2002-12-12/entertainment/18208286_1_four-album-deal-tim-mcgraw-carey-cd|title=Charmed Debut for Carey CD|last=Farber|first=Jim|date=December 12, 2002|newspaper=[[Daily News (New York)|New York Daily News]]|publisher=[[Mortimer Zuckerman]]|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20120614051944/http://articles.nydailynews.com/2002-12-12/entertainment/18208286_1_four-album-deal-tim-mcgraw-carey-cd|archivedate=June 14, 2012|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> It stayed on the chart for 22 weeks,<ref name="billboard1">{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=mariah carey|chart=all}}|title=Charmbracelet&nbsp;<U+2013> Mariah Carey|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> ''Charmbracelet'' was certified Platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA) for shipments of one million units in the US.<ref name="riaa">{{cite web|url=http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?content_selector=gold-platinum-searchable-database|title=Gold & Platinum: Searchable Database|publisher=Recording Industry Association of America|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> {{As of|April 2013}}, the estimated sales of the album in the US (compiled by [[Nielsen Soundscan]]) were 1,166,000 copies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://new.music.yahoo.com/blogs/chart_watch/70544/week-ending-dec-5-2010-the-gift-that-keeps-on-giving/|title=Week Ending Dec.&nbsp;5,&nbsp;2010: The 'Gift' That Keeps on Giving|last=Grien|first=Paul|work=[[Yahoo! Music]]|publisher=[[Yahoo! Inc.|Yahoo! Inc]]|date=December 8, 2010|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/1555095/ask-billboard-belindas-back-jt-too-mariah-careys-album-sales?page=0%2C2|title=Ask Billboard: Belinda's Back, JT Too, Mariah Carey's Album Sales & More|last=Trust|first=Gary|date=2013-04-02|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media |accessdate=2013-05-11}}</ref>

In Canada, the album debuted on the [[Canadian Albums Chart]] outside the top 20, in contrast to ''Glitter'', which debuted at number four on the chart.<ref name="canada">{{cite web|url=http://jam.canoe.ca/Music/Artists/C/Carey_Mariah/2002/12/11/743778.html|title=Mariah Can't Charm Canadians|last=Williams|first=John|work=[[Jam!]]|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]] ([[Sun Media]])|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> It was certified Gold by the [[Canadian Recording Industry Association]] (CRIA) for shipments of 50,000 copies.<ref name="cria">{{cite web|url=http://www.musiccanada.com/GPSearchResult.aspx?st=Charmbracelet&ica=False&sa=Mariah%20Carey&sl=&smt=0&sat=-1&ssb=Artist|title=Gold and Platinum Search|publisher=[[Music Canada]]|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> On the week dated December 15, 2002, ''Chamrbracelet'' entered the [[Australian Albums Chart]] at its peak position of number 42.<ref name="australia">{{cite web|url=http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Mariah+Carey&titel=Charmbracelet&cat=a|title=Mariah Carey&nbsp;<U+2013> Charmbracelet|work=[[ARIA Charts]]|publisher=Hung Medien|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> It exited the chart the next week, becoming one of Carey's lowest charting albums in the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://australian-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Mariah+Carey|title=Discography of Mariah Carey|work=ARIA Charts|publisher=Hung Medien|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> In Japan, ''Charmbracelet'' debuted at number four on the [[Oricon|Oricon Albums Chart]], its second-highest peak worldwide, and sold 63,365 units in its first week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/search/result.php?kbn=ja&types=rnk&year=2002&month=12&week=1&submit5.x=30&submit5.y=17|title=<U+691C><U+7D22><U+7D50><U+679C>-ORICON STYLE <U+30A2><U+30FC><U+30C6><U+30A3><U+30B9><U+30C8>/CD<U+691C><U+7D22>|publisher=[[Oricon]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> The album spent another week at number four, and sold 71,206 units.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/search/result.php?kbn=ja&types=rnk&year=2002&month=12&week=2&submit5.x=30&submit5.y=17|title=<U+691C><U+7D22><U+7D50><U+679C>-ORICON STYLE <U+30A2><U+30FC><U+30C6><U+30A3><U+30B9><U+30C8>/CD<U+691C><U+7D22>|publisher=Oricon|language=Japanese|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> It stayed on the charts for a total of 15 weeks and according to Oricon, has sold 240,440 copies.<ref name="japanp">{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/prof/artist/163336/ranking/cd_album/|title=<U+30DE><U+30E9><U+30A4><U+30A2><U+30FB><U+30AD><U+30E3><U+30EA><U+30FC><U+306E>CD<U+30A2><U+30EB><U+30D0><U+30E0><U+30E9><U+30F3><U+30AD><U+30F3><U+30B0><U+3001><U+30DE><U+30E9><U+30A4><U+30A2><U+30FB><U+30AD><U+30E3><U+30EA><U+30FC><U+306E><U+30D7><U+30ED><U+30D5><U+30A3><U+30FC><U+30EB><U+306A><U+3089><U+30AA><U+30EA><U+30B3><U+30F3><U+82B8><U+80FD><U+4EBA><U+4E8B><U+5178>-ORICON STYLE|publisher=Oricon|language=Japanese|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref><ref name="oricon1">{{cite web|url=http://ranking.oricon.co.jp/|title=<U+30AA><U+30EA><U+30B3><U+30F3><U+30E9><U+30F3><U+30AD><U+30F3><U+30B0><U+60C5><U+5831><U+30B5><U+30FC><U+30D3><U+30B9><U+300C>you<U+5927><U+6A39><U+300D><U+3000><U+FF0D>CD<U+30FB><U+30D6><U+30EB><U+30FC><U+30EC><U+30A4><U+30FB>DVD<U+30FB><U+66F8><U+7C4D><U+30FB><U+30B3><U+30DF><U+30C3><U+30AF><U+FF0D>|publisher=Oricon|language=Japanese|format=Subsription required|accessdate=September 26, 2011}}</ref> The [[Recording Industry Association of Japan]] (RIAJ) certified ''Charmbracelet'' platinum for shipments of 250,000 copies.<ref name="riaj">{{cite web|url=http://www.riaj.or.jp/issue/record/2003/200301_02.pdf|title=The Record: Recording Industry Association of Japan|publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of Japan]]|format=PDF|accessdate=September 26, 2011}}</ref>

In Austria, the album peaked at number 34 and stayed on the charts for seven weeks.<ref name="austria">{{cite web|url=http://austriancharts.at/showitem.asp?interpret=Mariah+Carey&titel=Charmbracelet&cat=a|title=Mariah Carey&nbsp;<U+2013> Charmbracelet|work=[[<U+00D6>3 Austria Top 40]]|publisher=Hung Median|language=German|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> In the Flemish region of Belgium it charted and peaked at number 48 and reached number 28 in the Walloon region of that country.<ref name="flanders">{{cite web|url=http://www.ultratop.be/nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Mariah+Carey&titel=Charmbracelet&cat=a|title=Mariah Carey&nbsp;<U+2013> Charmbracelet|work=[[Ultratop]]|publisher=Hung Medien|language=Dutch|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref><ref name="wallonia">{{cite web|url=http://www.ultratop.be/fr/showitem.asp?interpret=Mariah+Carey&titel=Charmbracelet&cat=a|title=Mariah Carey&nbsp;<U+2013> Charmbracelet|work=Ultratop|publisher=Hung Medien|language=Dutch|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> ''Charmbracelet'' entered the [[French Albums Chart]] at number 20 in the week dated December 7, 2002,<ref name="france">{{cite web|url=http://lescharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Mariah+Carey&titel=Charmbracelet&cat=a|title=Mariah Carey&nbsp;<U+2013> Charmbracelet|work=''[[Syndicat National de l'<U+00C9>dition Phonographique|French Albums Chart]]''|publisher=Hung Medien|language=French|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> spent 30 weeks on the chart<ref name="france"/> and was certified Gold by the [[Syndicat National de l'<U+00C9>dition Phonographique]] (SNEP), denoting shipments of 150,000 units.<ref name="snep">{{cite web|url=http://www.disqueenfrance.com/fr/pag-259165-CERTIFICATIONS.html?year=2003&type=8|title=Certifications Albums Or&nbsp;<U+2013> ann<U+00E9>e 2003 |work=Disqueenfrance|publisher=Syndicat National de l'<U+00C9>dition Phonographique|language=French|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.infodisc.fr/Certif_Album.php|title=Les Certifications (Albums) du SNEP|publisher=InfoDisc. Syndicat National de l'<U+00C9>dition Phonographique|format=Select CAREY M. from the drop down menu and click GO|language=French|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> ''Charmbracelet'' charted and peaked at number 32 in Germany<ref name="germany">{{cite web|url=http://www.musicline.de/de/chartverfolgung_summary/artist/Carey%2CMariah/?type=longplay|title=Carey, Mariah > Chartverfolgung > Longplay|publisher=[[Media Control Charts]]|language=German|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> It reached number 50 in Sweden.<ref name="sweden">{{cite web|url=http://swedishcharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Mariah+Carey&titel=Charmbracelet&cat=a|title=Mariah Carey&nbsp;<U+2013> Charmbracelet|work=[[Sverigetopplistan]]|publisher=Hung Medien|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> In Switzerland, the album peaked at number nine on the [[Swiss Albums Chart]] and stayed on the charts for ten weeks;<ref name="swiss">{{cite web|url=http://swisscharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Mariah+Carey&titel=Charmbracelet&cat=a|title=Mariah Carey&nbsp;<U+2013> Charmbracelet|work=[[Swiss Music Charts]]|publisher=Hung Medien|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> it was certified Gold by the [[International Federation of the Phonographic Industry]] (IFPI).<ref name="ifpiswiss">{{cite web|url=http://www.swisscharts.com/awards.asp?year=2003|title=Awards 2003|work=Swiss Music Charts|publisher=Hung Medien|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> In the United Kingdom, the album peaked at number 52, selling 19,000 copies in its first week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://business.highbeam.com/411456/article-1G1-96194690/official-uk-albums-charts-top-75|title=The Official UK Albums: Chart Top 75|last=Jones|first=Alan|work=[[Music Week]]|publisher=[[UBM plc|United Business Media]]|format=Subscription required|date=December 14, 2002|accessdate=August 31, 2012}}</ref> It has sold a total of 122,010 copies as of April 2008.<ref name="ukc">{{cite web|url=http://www.musicweek.com/story.asp?storyCode=1033970&sectioncode=1|title=Kooks Top Albums Chart with First Week Sales of 65,901|last=Jones|first=Alan|work=Music Week|publisher=United Business Media|date=April 21, 2008|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> In February 2003, it was certified Gold by the [[British Phonographic Industry]] (BPI) for sales/shipments of 100,000 copies in the UK.<ref name="bpi">{{cite web|url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/certifiedawards/search.aspx|title=Certified Awards Search|publisher=[[British Phonographic Industry]]|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> In the Netherlands, the album debuted at number 48, the issue dated December 14, 2002. The following week, it peaked at number 30. It stayed on the charts for 19 weeks, and made two re-entries, one in June 2003 and other in August 2003.<ref name="dutch">{{cite web|url=http://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Mariah+Carey&titel=Charmbracelet&cat=a|title=Mariah Carey&nbsp;<U+2013> Charmbracelet|work=[[Dutch Top 40]]|publisher=Hung Medien|language=Dutch|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref>

''Charmbracelet'' was certified Gold in both Brazil and Hong Kong by [[Associa<U+00E7><U+00E3>o Brasileira dos Produtores de Discos]] (ABPD) and IFPI Hong Kong respectively.<ref name="brazil">{{cite web|url=http://www.abpd.org.br/certificados.asp|title=Certificados|publisher=Associa<U+00E7><U+00E3>o Brasileira dos Produtores de Discos|language=Portuguese|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref><ref name="hongkong">{{cite web|url=http://www.ifpihk.org/www_1/go21e.php|title=<U+9999><U+6E2F><U+5531><U+7247><U+92B7><U+91CF><U+5927><U+734E> 2003|publisher=International Federation of the Phonographic Industry|language=Chinese|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20120219071137/http://www.ifpihk.org/www_1/go21e.php|archivedate=February 19, 2012|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref>
As to date, it has sold 5 million copies worldwide.

==Promotion==
[[File:Mariah Carey 2003 tour 1.jpg|left|thumb|Carey performing "Hero" live during her [[Charmbracelet World Tour: An Intimate Evening with Mariah Carey|Charmbracelet World Tour]] (2003<U+2013>04)|alt=A blonde woman wearing a white gown sings. Behind her are brightly lit stairs, and twinkling lights are on the ceiling.]]

Following the release of "Through the Rain", Carey embarked on several US and international promotional tours in support of ''Charmbracelet'' and its accompanying singles. Promotion for "Through the Rain" began at the 2002 [[NRJ Awards]], where Carey performed wearing a long black skirt and denim blazer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leparisien.fr/loisirs-et-spectacles/tf-1-et-nrj-ont-toutes-les-stars-18-01-2003-2003742780.php|title=TF1 And TRJ Are All Stars!|last=Catroux|first=Sebastian|work=Le Parisien |location=France|publisher=[[<U+00C9>ditions Philippe Amaury]]|date=January 18, 2003|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6DaeJFxwT|archivedate=2013-01-11|accessdate=June 15, 2011}}{{dead link|date=November 2011}}</ref> Three days before the album's US release, a one-hour program titled ''Mariah Carey: Shining Through the Rain'', in which Carey was interviewed and sang several songs from ''Charmbracelet'' and her back catalog, aired on [[MTV]].<ref name=sttr/> Carey addressed rumors of her breakdown and its cause, and spoke about the album and its inspiration, and conducted a question and answer session with fans.<ref name=sttr>{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=wM0gAAAAIBAJ&sjid=eWoFAAAAIBAJ&pg=5892,112208|title=Mariah Glittering Again|newspaper=[[Sun Journal (Lewiston)|Sun Journal]]|publisher=Sun Media Group|date=December 2, 2001|page=C14|accessdate=June 15, 2011}}</ref> During the first month after the album's release, Carey appeared on several television talk shows. She launched her promotional tour on ''[[Today (NBC program)|Today]]'', where she performed four songs at [[Mall of America]] for a crowd of over 10,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=PD&s_site=twincities&p_multi=SP&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0F90A465D2DC895D&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=A Mega Turnout, Carey Chooses Mall of America for Live Show; 10,000 Hear Her|last=Samuel|first=James|newspaper=[[St. Paul Pioneer Press]]|publisher=[[MediaNews Group]]|date=December 12, 2002|accessdate=June 15, 2011}}</ref> On December 2, Carey traveled to Brazil for South American promotion of ''Charmbracelet'', appearing on the popular television program ''[[Fant<U+00E1>stico]]''. She sang "My All", and performed "Through the Rain" and "I Only Wanted" wearing a long pink gown.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.terra.com.br/exclusivo/noticias/2002/12/05/008.htm|title=Mariah Carey Grava Show Para o Fant<U+00E1>stico ao Lado de Sandy|publisher=[[Terra Networks]]|language=Portuguese|date=December 5, 2002|accessdate=June 15, 2011}}</ref> On December 3, 2002, Carey appeared on ''[[The Oprah Winfrey Show]]'', where she performed "Through the Rain" and "My Saving Grace", and gave a highly publicized interview about her hospitalization.<ref name=promo>{{cite news|url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2002-11-26/entertainment/18205612_1_new-record-glitter-mariah-carey|title=A Whirlwind Called Mariah|last=Huff|first=Richard|newspaper=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]|publisher=[[Mortimer Zuckerman]]|date=November 26, 2001|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20120612045229/http://articles.nydailynews.com/2002-11-26/entertainment/18205612_1_new-record-glitter-mariah-carey|archivedate=June 12, 2012|accessdate=June 15, 2011}}</ref> Before her breakdown, Carey had been booked for a private interview with ABC's Barbara Walters, executive producer of ''[[The View (U.S. TV series)|The View]]'', following ''Glitter''{{'}}s release.<ref name=promo/> Instead of giving Walters the full-coverage interview following Carey's return to the public eye, Island decided ''Oprah'' was more appropriate, and changed the appearance.<ref name=promo/> Carey's interview with [[Matt Lauer]] on ''[[Dateline NBC]]'' aired the same evening.<ref name=promo/>

On December 17, Carey performed "I Only Wanted" on ''The View'' after guest co-hosting the program.<ref name=promo/> One month later, Carey was one of the headlining performers at the [[American Music Awards of 2003|30th]] annual [[American Music Award]]s, held on January 13, 2003.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2003-01-14/entertainment/18227963_1_male-artist-hip-hop-favorite-pop|title=Good Show? Yes, Of Curse|last=Guzman|first=Isaac|newspaper=Daily News|publisher=Mortimer Zuckerman|date=January 14, 2003|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20120612045233/http://articles.nydailynews.com/2003-01-14/entertainment/18227963_1_male-artist-hip-hop-favorite-pop|archivedate=June 12, 2012|accessdate=June 15, 2011}}</ref> She performed "Through the Rain" alongside a live gospel choir, and wore a long black evening gown.<ref name=ama>{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=VBVSAAAAIBAJ&sjid=PDUNAAAAIBAJ&pg=4056,2384781|title=Big Winners No-Shows At American Music Awards|work=[[Times Union (Albany)|Times Union]]|publisher=Hearst Corporation|page=6B|date=January 14, 2003|accessdate=June 15, 2011}}</ref> During the performance, images of newspaper headlines reporting Carey's breakdown were projected on a large curtain behind her, with one reading, "When you fall down, you get back up."<ref name=ama/> Carey received a standing ovation.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/orlandosentinel/access/276959101.html?dids=276959101:276959101&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jan+14%2C+2003&author=&pub=Orlando+Sentinel&desc=AMA+AWARDS+BRING+OUT+--+AND+BLEEP+--++THE+STARS&pqatl=google|title=AMA Awards Bring Out&nbsp;<U+2013> And Bleep&nbsp;<U+2013> The Stars|newspaper=[[Orlando Sentinel]]|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|page=A4|date=January 14, 2003|accessdate=August 29, 2011}}</ref> In mid-February, Carey was the headline performer at the [[NBA]] all-star game, which was [[Michael Jordan]]'s last game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2003/02/10/national/main539973.shtml|title=Jordan Bows Out In Style, Not In Victory|work=[[CBS News]]|publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|date=February 11, 2009|accessdate=June 15, 2011}}</ref> She wore a long, purple, skin-tight Washington Wizard's dress, and performed "Boy (I Need You)", "My Saving Grace" and "[[Hero (Mariah Carey song)|Hero]]", which received a standing ovation and brought Jordan to tears.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=yRtlAAAAIBAJ&sjid=BIcNAAAAIBAJ&pg=942,4333992&dq=mariah+carey+michael+jordan+tribute&hl=en|title=Mariah Carey to Perform Special Tribute to Michael Jordan at the 2003 NBA All-Star Game|work=[[Business Wire]]|publisher=[[Berkshire Hathaway]]|date=February 5, 2003|accessdate=June 15, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=yRtlAAAAIBAJ&sjid=BIcNAAAAIBAJ&pg=942,4333992|title=A Fitting Farewell To A Legend|last=Lommers|first=Aaron|work=The South Seattle Sentinel|publisher=The South Seattle Sentinel Company|page=11|date=February 21, 2003|accessdate=June 15, 2011}}</ref> On March 1, 2003, Carey performed at the [[2003 Soul Train Music Awards|Soul Train Music Awards]], sporting a retro-curled hairstyle and wearing a burgundy evening gown.<ref name=promo3>{{cite news|url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/thestar/access/430509981.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Mar+03%2C+2003&author=&pub=Waterloo+Region+Record&desc=Ashanti%2C+Musiq+win+top+Soul+Train+Awards&pqatl=google|title=Ashanti, Musiq Win Top Soul Train Awards|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|publisher=[[Torstar]]|date=March 3, 2003|accessdate=June 15, 2011}}</ref> She performed "My Saving Grace", and as at the American Music Awards, images of newspaper headlines and inspirational photographs were projected onto a large screen.<ref name=promo3/> Following the performance, Carey was awarded a lifetime achievement award for her contribution to music.<ref name=promo3/> Towards the end of March, ''Charmbracelet'' was released in Europe and Carey appeared on several television programs to promotion the album.<ref name=pops>{{cite news|url=http://articles.sfgate.com/2003-03-27/entertainment/17479662_1_calvin-klein-jennifer-lopez-dinner-guest|title=Mariah Brings Her Own Cook|newspaper=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|publisher=Hearst Corporation|date=March 27, 2003|accessdate=June 15, 2011}}</ref> She performed the album's leading two singles on the British music chart show, ''[[Top of the Pops]]'', and a similar set on ''[[The Graham Norton Show]]'' and ''[[Fame Academy]]''.<ref name=pops/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/smgpubs/access/318932601.html?dids=318932601:318932601&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Mar+27%2C+2003&author=&pub=Evening+Times&desc=Mariah+is+all+a-flutter&pqatl=google|title=Mariah Is All A-Flutter|newspaper=[[Evening Times]]|publisher=[[Newsquest]]|date=March 27, 2003|accessdate=June 16, 2011}}</ref><ref name=ukpromo>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/2439239.stm|title=Fame Academy Wins More Viewers|work=[[BBC News]]|publisher=BBC  |date=March 30, 2003|accessdate=June 16, 2011}}</ref> On the latter program, Carey was joined on stage by the show's finalists, who sang the climax on "Through the Rain" alongside her.<ref name=ukpromo/>

===Tour===
[[File:Mariah Carey 2003 tour 3.jpg|right|thumb|Carey performing "Subtle Invitation", seated on top of a piano, on the Charmbracelet Tour (2003<U+2013>04)|alt=A blonde woman sits atop a piano and sings. A long, white cloth hangs around her while a silhouette behind the woman shows two male figures as if holding the white cloth.]]

To promote the album, Carey announced a world tour in April 2003.<ref name=vh1>{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/news/articles/1472736/20030616/index.jhtml|title=Carey Maps Out 'Intimate Evening' Tour |last=Patel |first = Joseph |work=[[VH1]]|publisher=[[MTV Networks]] ([[Viacom]])|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20040114013954/http://www.vh1.com/news/articles/1472736/20030616/carey_mariah.jhtml?headlines=true|archivedate = January 14, 2004| accessdate = June 15, 2011}}</ref> {{as of|2003}}, "[[Charmbracelet World Tour: An Intimate Evening with Mariah Carey]]" was her most extensive tour, lasting over eight months and performing sixty-nine shows in venues worldwide.<ref name=vh2>{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/news/articles/1471917/mariah-carey-scraps-arena-tour.jhtml|title=Mariah Carey Scraps Arena Tour, Opts To Get More Intimate |last=Patel |first=Joseph |work=VH1 |publisher=MTV Networks (Viacom) |accessdate=June 15, 2011}}</ref> Before tickets went on sale in the US, venues were switched from large arenas to smaller, more intimate theater shows. According to Carey, the change was made in order to give fans a more intimate show, and something more Broadway-influenced. She said, "It's much more intimate so you'll feel like you had an experience. You experience a night with me."<ref name=vh1/> However, while smaller productions were booked for the US leg of the tour, Carey performed at stadia and arenas in Asia and Europe, and performed for a crowd of over 35,000 in Manila, 50,000 in Malaysia, and to over 70,000 people in China.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SJ&s_site=mercurynews&p_multi=SJ&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=1002404456D02378&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=Mariah's Malaysia Concert Ill-timed, Says Muslim Leader|newspaper=[[San Jose Mercury News]]|publisher=[[MediaNews Group]]|date=January 16, 2004|accessdate=June 15, 2011}}</ref> In the UK, it was Carey's first tour to feature shows outside London; she performed in Glasgow, Birmingham and Manchester.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/2932336.stm|title=Mariah Adds UK To World Tour|work=[[BBC News]]|publisher=BBC  |date=May 31, 2003|accessdate=February 3, 2011}}</ref>

"Charmbracelet World Tour: An Intimate Evening with Mariah Carey" garnered generally positive reviews from music critics and audiences, many of whom complimented the quality of Carey's live vocals and the production of the shows. Fans were given the opportunity to request songs from Carey's catalog, which added to its positive reception.<ref name=vh2/> At her concert in Manila, Rito P. Asilo from ''[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]'' wrote, "I didn't expect her voice to be that crystal clear!"<ref name=asilo>{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=9LhjAAAAIBAJ&sjid=eyUMAAAAIBAJ&pg=1866,15841802|title=Mariah Carey Thrills Euphoric Manila Crowd|last=Asilo|first=Rito P.|work=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]|publisher=Philippine Daily Inquirer, Inc.|date=November 23, 2003|page=I3|accessdate=June 13, 2011}}</ref> He added, "After 15 songs, we couldn't seem to get enough of Mariah{{emdash}}and we became a believer!".<ref name=asilo/>

==Re-release==
While preparing for the Asian leg of the Charmbracelet World Tour, Carey announced that ''Charmbraclet'' would be re-released with four additional tracks<ref name="Vineyard1">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1472062/mariah-carey-revamping-latest-lp.jhtml|title=Mariah Carey Adding Some New Charms To Her Bracelet|publisher=[[MTV News]]. [[Viacom]]|accessdate=February 24, 2011|date=June 18, 2003|first=Jennifer|last=Vineyard}}</ref> on July 26, 2003, the first day of the North American leg of the tour.<ref name=colo>{{cite news|title=Mariah Her Own Master|work=[[The Columbian]]|publisher=Columbian Publishing Corporation|date=June 20, 2003}}</ref>  Carey included her duet with [[Busta Rhymes]], "[[I Know What You Want]]", which was released as a single from his album, ''[[It Ain't Safe No More]]'' (2002),<ref name=chic>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2003-07-31/features/0307310233_1_intimate-arenas-glitter|title=Stylish Carey Strains to Find Soul|last=Klein|first=Joshua|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|date=June 15, 2002|accessdate=May 12, 2011}}</ref> and became Carey's highest charting song internationally since 2001, reaching top five peaks in Australia, Canada, the Netherlands, Ireland, Italy, Switzerland, the US and the UK.<ref name=mcultra>{{cite web|url=http://www.ultratop.be/en/showitem.asp?interpret=Busta+Rhymes+and+Mariah+Carey+feat%2E+The+Flipmode+Squad&titel=I+Know+What+You+Want&cat=s|title=Mariah Carey <U+2013> I Know What You Want|publisher=[[Ultratop]]. Hung Medien|language=German|accessdate=May 13, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://allmusic.com/album/it-aint-safe-no-more-r617106/charts-awards/billboard-single|title=It Ain's Safe No More <U+2013> Busta Rhymes > ''Billboard'' Singles|publisher=Allmusic. Rovi Corporation|accessdate=September 2, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theofficialcharts.com/artist/_/busta%20rhymes/|title=Busta Rhymes|publisher=The Official Charts Company|accessdate=September 2, 2011}}</ref> In an interview with [[Carson Daly]], Carey said, "The Busta Rhymes duet&nbsp;...&nbsp;has become so successful and we always said I would put it on my album as well."<ref name="Vineyard1"/> The re-release also included "There Goes My Heart", "Got a Thing 4 You" featuring [[Da Brat]] and [[Elephant Man (musician)|Elephant Man]], and "The One (So So Def Remix)" featuring [[Bone Crusher]].<ref>{{cite interview|last=Carey|first=Mariah|subjectlink=Mariah Carey|interviewer=[[Carson Daly]]|program=[[Total Request Live]]|callsign=[[MTV]]|city=[[New York]]|date=June 18, 2003|accessdate=September 2, 2011}}</ref> The re-released version of the album charted for three weeks on the Oricon album chart in Japan, where it peaked at number 96 on the issue dated July 14, 2003.<ref name="oricon1"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/prof/artist/163336/products/music/505474/1/|title=<U+30C1><U+30E3><U+30FC><U+30E0><U+30D6><U+30EC><U+30B9><U+30EC><U+30C3><U+30C8><U+30FB><U+30C4><U+30A2><U+30FC><U+30FB><U+30A8><U+30C7><U+30A3><U+30B7><U+30E7><U+30F3> <U+30DE><U+30E9><U+30A4><U+30A2><U+30FB><U+30AD><U+30E3><U+30EA><U+30FC><U+306E><U+30D7><U+30ED><U+30D5><U+30A3><U+30FC><U+30EB><U+306A><U+3089><U+30AA><U+30EA><U+30B3><U+30F3><U+82B8><U+80FD><U+4EBA><U+4E8B><U+5178>-ORICON STYLE|publisher=Oricon|language=Japanese|accessdate=September 26, 2011}}</ref>

==Awards==
At the 17th [[Japan Gold Disc Award]] in 2003, the album was nominated in the category of Rock and Pop Album of the Year (International).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.riaj.or.jp/e/data/gdisc/2003.html|title=The 17th Japan Gold Disc Award 2003|publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of Japan]]|accessdate=August 29, 2011}}</ref>{{clear}}

